text:
Sure thing.  How I came to like lighting a bit more is just through experimentation. Trying a few different specialisms. And founds the ones I avoid, the ones I don't mind doing and the ones I like. I chose lighting more as I like creating different atmospheres and moods with the types of lights and colours. 

What I do here at bluezoo is basically use light rigs and set up scenes to make sure the lighting hooks up with the environment and stays continuous throughiut the scene. The extra bit is comp is combining the render layers we have. So here it is character layer and then environment and shadows.  Also effects gets added in this layer as well
Once all the layers are kind of added is when you can kind of get a sense of how it's looking

Does it take long to set up a scene? Since I have never had an experience I can't imagine what you do for 40 hrs a week whole year. Is it like you always have something to do? Or does it depends on availability of projects?

I know from some studio they have quiet spells and intensive ones. For me it kind of just constant pace. Um. Not really some shots can be set up really quickly. Like you may to shots which look nearly identical in the position and framing. So you just do one and copy it over. The other parts which need to get setup like the setting and render layer doesn't take long we have tools to do that.
But also depends on how heavy the scenes are. Some of the scenes are quite heavy.
But that just means more time it takes to render.
Is render time part of working time? Do u render during work or leave it over night?
Also when is the best to contact u?
When ever.
I don't really mind. If I have Tien I'll answer

It's mixed so when I'm working on shots I render during work time. When I think the lighting is good I send it to farm to either render it over night or on render it in working hours depending on priority and availability of blades
Do you have a render farm at your university
I know some do and some don't
What is render farm? :^)
We use just PCs uni provides. So we model and render on same pc.
And what os availability of blades?
Is*

Ah ok. I'll give it a good at explaining but they are made in a few different ways.  kind of think of it as big room full of computers. Say 100 computers/blades. If I send a job to the farm of a shot about 20 frames. I can 1 frame to 20 blades. So if one frame takes 10 minutes and can complete my 20 frames in that time. Rather than it taking 20p minutes. While these are working I still have 80 blades still available for the next person to use. Priorities as you can guess decided who gets the blades or the other people. But you may find people at uni do like a mini farm. So like logging onto multiple pc and splitting the job across them. However. Not as good as a normal farm as your taking pc away from pc and depending how your saving your dating you have to go and collect it from all the pcs in the end.
Basically. I could have explained it like this. A load of pc connected to each by a network
However. If you're looking at real time rendering in games. It wouldn't really benefit much
Ah, gotcha
Last year final year student took 7 pcs for his final render. Quite annoying since pcs he took were in the middle of the room where usually ppl work

However if you wanna try linking computers up across the network. Just remember. The data will be slower transfering across the network and you might bring the network down like we nearly did by sending too much data at once
And in BlueZoo how you decide who takes blades?
Too much data? So one pc renders different projects at the same time?
Well if your uni works likes how ours did not to be mean but if you need a pc just turn one of them off
Nah like. Sending 4gb scene files to different pcs

It's kinda nasty to turn them off :D 
Usually there is paper "I am rendering pls dont touch"

But yeah when people did that with our computer in my years  room I made a few rules. Find another computer. If all are taken the people who's room it was belongs to takes priority. With their rendering and tirn off the people who shouldn't be there. And notify them.

And ppl feel kinda bad to turn it off. 
That guy's final project was huge scene made in maya. He did smt like hirez turntable camera. Since it was his *final* work everyone understood
